  "slug": "chicken-fajitas",
  "title": "Chicken fajitas",
  "subtitle": "Marinated thigh strips, peppers, soft tortillas at the table.",
  "excerpt": "Strips of marinated chicken thigh seared fast in a screaming-hot pan with sliced peppers and onion, brought to the table sizzling. Warm tortillas, soured cream, salsa, and a wedge of lime alongside. Build to taste.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "The fajita technique developed from the Mexican-American ranch kitchens of South Texas in the early twentieth century, where skirt steak (the original cut) was marinated and grilled. The chicken version came later as a popular substitute.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Boneless chicken thigh cut into 2 cm strips, marinated for an hour in lime juice, oil, garlic, and dried spice. The pan goes on the highest heat until it smokes faintly. Chicken in first, in a single layer, left alone for 3 minutes to catch colour. Pulled out into a warm dish. Peppers and onion go in next, charred fast, then the chicken returns for 2 more minutes to bind everything together.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Thigh meat over breast. Thighs stay juicy at the speed this dish demands; breast turns to chalk.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
