      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A cast-iron pan is the right tool: it holds the high heat and gives the proper char. Anything thinner will lose temperature when the chicken hits.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Marinate the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Squeeze the juice of 2 of the limes into a large bowl. Whisk in {{olive-oil}} of olive oil, {{garlic}} of chopped garlic, {{cumin-ground}} of cumin, {{paprika-smoked}} of smoked paprika, {{oregano-dried}} of oregano, {{chilli-flakes}} of chilli flakes if using, {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, and {{black-pepper}} of pepper. Add the {{chicken-thigh}} of chicken strips and turn to coat. Cover and refrigerate for 60 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Sear the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the cast-iron pan over the highest setting until you can see a faint haze. Lift the chicken from the marinade with tongs, letting excess drip off. Spread in a single layer in the pan; don't crowd. Cook 3 minutes without moving, until the underside is dark gold. Turn and cook 2 minutes more. Tip into a warm serving dish, cover loosely.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Char the peppers and onion",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Wipe the pan with kitchen paper. Return to high heat. Add {{vegetable-oil}} of oil and tip in {{pepper-red}} of red pepper, {{pepper-green}} of green pepper, and {{onion}} of sliced onion. Cook for 5 minutes, stirring once or twice, until charred at the edges and still crisp in the middle. Tip back into the dish with the chicken and toss together.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Warm the tortillas",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stack the tortillas, wrap in a clean tea towel, and microwave for 30 seconds; or warm in a dry frying pan, 15 seconds a side. Wrap in foil or a tea towel to hold the warmth.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Serve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bring everything to the table at once: the sizzling chicken-and-pepper dish, the warm tortillas, the soured cream, the wedges of lime, and the chopped coriander. Build each taco at the table.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Cook in two batches if the pan is small. The chicken should hiss audibly the moment it hits the pan.",
              "cause": "Pan too crowded, or temperature too low.",
              "symptom": "Chicken stewed not charred"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Slice peppers 1 cm thick. Five minutes total in the hot pan is enough; they should still have bite.",
              "cause": "Cooked too long, or sliced too thin.",
              "symptom": "Peppers soft and limp"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use boneless thigh; it stays juicy at high heat. Pull off the pan at 5 minutes total.",
              "cause": "Breast used instead of thigh, or overcooked.",
              "symptom": "Chicken dry"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Warm the tortillas just before serving and wrap in a tea towel. Two tablespoons of filling per tortilla, not more.",
              "cause": "Tortillas too cold, or filled too generously.",
              "symptom": "Tortillas tore at the table"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fajitas were Mexican ranch food in the Rio Grande Valley, where the throwaway skirt steak from the day's beef butcher was tossed with onion and grilled over wood. They reached the national American palate in the 1980s through restaurants in San Antonio and Austin. Drink a margarita with salt on the rim, or a cold Mexican lager.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
